fieldGroups.name: IBAN
fieldGroups.title: IBAN
fieldGroups.tooltip: IBANs are long account numbers used by banks for cross-border transfers. Each country structures this number differently, but it always starts with a 2 digit country code (e.g. DE for Germany).

fieldGroups.name: BIC
fieldGroups.title: Bank code (BIC/SWIFT)
fieldGroups.tooltip: The BIC (SWIFT code) is used to identify a bank when making cross-border money transfers. It’s 8-11 characters long and often includes part of the bank’s name.

fieldGroups.name: clearingNumber
fieldGroups.title: Clearing number
fieldGroups.tooltip: Swedish clearing number.

fieldGroups.name: accountNumber
fieldGroups.title: Account number
fieldGroups.tooltip: Swedish local account number (without a clearing number).

fieldGroups.name: abartn
fieldGroups.title: ACH routing number
fieldGroups.info: This is the routing number used for local ACH transfers between banks in the US. The final recipient bank account needs to be in the USA.

fieldGroups.name: swiftCode
fieldGroups.title: SWIFT code
fieldGroups.tooltip: The SWIFT code uniquely identifies a bank. It’s 8-11 characters long, contains a country code and often includes a part of the bank’s name.

fieldGroups.name: institution
fieldGroups.title: Institution No.
fieldGroups.tooltip: The institution number is a 3-digit number identifying the financial institution to which a payment item is directed. Along with the account number, it is essential for delivering payments through the clearing system. If you don't know the institution number of the beneficiary bank please try to locate it here.

fieldGroups.name: BIC
fieldGroups.title: Bank code (BIC/SWIFT)
fieldGroups.tooltip: The BIC (SWIFT code) is used to identify a bank when making cross-border money transfers. It’s 8-11 characters long and often includes part of the bank’s name.

fieldGroups.name: bsbCode
fieldGroups.title: BSB code
fieldGroups.tooltip: The Bank State Branch code (BSB) identifies the bank and branch holding a bank account in Australia. It’s 6 digits long and there’s no need to include the dash in the middle.

fieldGroups.name: bsbCode
fieldGroups.title: BSB code
fieldGroups.tooltip: The Bank State Branch code (BSB) identifies the bank and branch holding a bank account in Australia. It’s 6 digits long and there’s no need to include the dash in the middle.

fieldGroups.name: businessNumber
fieldGroups.title: Business number
fieldGroups.tooltip: Australian business identification number issued by Australian Business Register, could be one of ACN, ABN or ARBN. You can search for the number here.

title: Indian local
nameTooltip: Please note that charity recipients are not supported.

fieldGroups.name: receiverType
fieldGroups.title: Recipient type
fieldGroups.tooltip: For business recipients maximum amount is 1 500 000 INR

fieldGroups.name: ifscCode
fieldGroups.title: IFSC Code
fieldGroups.tooltip: The Indian Financial System Code (IFSC) identifies the Indian bank branch. It’s 11 characters long, and used for RTGS and NEFT transfers. You can find your IFSC here.
